Conditional probability Conditional probability is when weâ€™re trying to consider two events that are related to each other. $$ P(A \mid B)= rac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)} $$ ğŸŒ° ä¸€ä¸ªä¾‹å­ï¼š30ä¸ªå­¦ç”Ÿï¼Œ9ä¸ªå¥³ç”Ÿï¼›12ä¸ªå­¦è®¡ç®—æœºï¼Œå­¦è®¡ç®—æœºä¸­4ä¸ªå¥³ç”Ÿã€‚ $$  egin{align*} & P(Female)= rac{9}{30}= rac{3}{10} 
ewline & P(CS)= rac{12}{30}= rac{2}{5} 
ewline & P(Female \cap CS)= rac{4}{30}= rac{2}{15} 
ewline & P(Female \mid CS)= rac{4}{12}= rac{1}{3} 
ewline \end{align*} $$ â‡’ $$  egin{align*} P(CS \mid Female) &=  rac{P(CS \cap Female)}{P(Female)} 
ewline & =  rac{ rac{2}{15}}{ rac{3}{10}}= rac{4}{9} 
ewline P(Female \mid CS^{\complement}) &=  rac{P(Female \cap CS^{\complement})}{P(CS^{\complement})} 
ewline &=  rac{ rac{5}{30}}{ rac{18}{30}}= rac{5}{18} \end{align*} $$ Thereâ€™s a concept of independence, which is when one event doesnâ€™t depend on the other. When two events are independent, we have that the probability of A given B is equal to just the probability of A, it doesnâ€™t matter whether, or not B occurred. When this is true, we also get that the probability of A and B happening is just the probability of A times the probability of B. äº‹ä»¶Aã€Bç‹¬ç«‹ï¼Œâ‡’ $P(A \mid B)=P(A)$ï¼› $P(A\cap B)=P(A) 	imes P(B)$
